0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHoarding has largely been approached from a psychological and universal perspective, and decluttering from an aesthetic and ecological one, while little work has been done to think about the cultural and global economic aspects of these phenomena. Of Hoarding and Housekeeping provides an anthropological, global, and comparative angle to the understanding of hoarding and decluttering using case studies from the likes of the US, Japan, India, and Argentina. Focusing on the house, with careful attention to material flows in and out, this book examines practices of accumulation, storage, decluttering, and waste as practices of kinship and the objects themselves as material kin.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCompulsive hoardingxSocial aspectsvCase studies2DLC. 0aCompulsive hoardingxSocial aspectsvCase studies. 0aKinshipvCase studies2DLC. 0aKinshipvCase studies. 0aMaterial culturevCase studies2DLC. 0aMaterial culturevCase studies. 0aStorage in the homexSocial aspectsvCase studies2DLC. 0aStorage in the homexSocial aspectsvCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aPolitical and Economic Anthropology, Sociology, Cultural Studies (General).1 aAngé, Olivia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlanco Esmoris, María Florencia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGould, Hannah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuitard, Émilie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGygi, Fabio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerrmann, Gretchen M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ct